tasks.description:
Goal: Finish the feature as a coherent operator experience with enough tests to protect default behavior and module-specific overrides.

Specific work:
- add config examples for common delivery and intake profiles;
- add explain output that shows why each policy value was selected;
- add end-to-end tests for default GitHub PR flow, local review delivery, default intake, strict intake on accept, and module overrides;
- verify migration/backward compatibility for existing deliveryEvidence v1 and improvement-task requirements;
- document any unsupported preference combinations with clear errors.

Blocked by: resolver, guard, CAE/readout, and docs tasks.

Goal: Stabilize runbooks around resolver-driven behavior for delivery and intake policy.

Specific work:
- update delivery playbooks to say resolve delivery policy, then follow resolved branch/review/merge/evidence steps;
- update task-engine command instructions to describe intake policy checks and resolver commands;
- document default profiles and supported preferences;
- update generated maintainer docs through the existing documentation pipeline if required;
- avoid hard-coding future preference values in runbooks beyond built-in defaults and examples.

Blocked by: delivery and intake resolver implementation tasks.

Goal: Make intake requirements visible to agents at decision time instead of relying on failed mutations or prose memory.

Specific work:
- include intake-policy guidance in create-task and accept-related command responses;
- add CAE guidance cards for missing required/recommended fields;
- include task intake policy summaries in agent-bootstrap/get-next-actions where relevant;
- avoid noisy guidance when the task already satisfies the policy;
- provide concise examples of fields the agent should add.

Blocked by: Task Engine: Resolve Task Intake Policy.

Goal: Ensure agents receive delivery-policy direction through the CLI and CAE exactly when they need it.

Specific work:
- include resolved delivery policy in maintainerDelivery readouts;
- preserve existing maintainerDeliveryProfile and requiresPhaseBranch hints;
- update CAE guidance cards to cite the resolved review mode, branch target, and evidence mode;
- keep network-free behavior for dashboard summaries;
- show policy warnings when module/task overrides conflict.

Blocked by: Task Engine: Resolve Maintainer Delivery Policy.

Goal: Enforce or advise on required task fields at the moments that matter: opening a task and accepting a proposed task into the ready queue.

Specific work:
- run intake policy during create-task for proposed and ready tasks;
- run intake policy during run-transition accept from proposed to ready;
- support enforcement modes off, advisory, enforce-on-accept, and enforce;
- return structured warnings in advisory mode;
- block only when configured enforcement says to block.

Blocked by: Task Engine: Resolve Task Intake Policy.

Goal: Let workspaces and modules decide what information an agent must provide when opening a task or moving a proposed task to ready.

Specific work:
- implement resolve-task-intake-policy for create-task, create-ready, and accept proposed contexts;
- support requiredFields, recommendedFields, forbiddenFields, and fieldRules;
- support task type, module, category, phase, and lifecycle-action matching;
- preserve current default requirements and existing improvement-task guardrails;
- return missing field lists and source explanations.

Blocked by: Task Engine: Define Policy Configuration Contracts.

Goal: Close the loop between configurable delivery preferences and task completion evidence.

Specific work:
- resolve delivery policy for each task checked by phase-delivery-preflight;
- validate delivery evidence against the resolved evidence mode;
- keep enforcementMode off/advisory/enforce behavior;
- distinguish missing evidence from wrong evidence mode;
- report policy source and required evidence shape in preflight output.

Blocked by: Task Engine: Resolve Maintainer Delivery Policy and Task Engine: Add Delivery Evidence V2.

Goal: Support GitHub PR evidence and local/external review evidence with a versioned, policy-aware evidence model.

Specific work:
- accept existing deliveryEvidence schemaVersion 1 for compatibility;
- add deliveryEvidence schemaVersion 2 with mode discriminators;
- support modes such as github-pr, local-reviewed-merge, direct-reviewed-merge, and external-review;
- validate required fields per mode;
- keep deliveryWaiver as an exception path rather than the normal local-review path.

Blocked by: Task Engine: Define Policy Configuration Contracts.

Goal: Give agents and tools a single machine-readable source for how a task should be delivered.

Specific work:
- implement resolveMaintainerDeliveryPolicy for existing tasks and prospective task contexts;
- add workspace-kit run resolve-maintainer-delivery-policy;
- resolve branch patterns, review mode, PR provider, merge target, merge strategy, phase-to-main mode, tagging strategy, and evidence mode;
- explain source precedence for every selected value;
- preserve compatibility with task metadata hints while making config the preferred source.

Blocked by: Task Engine: Define Policy Configuration Contracts.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-23 as the bounded operator-docs and release-gate slice.

Goal: Make the MVP operable and releasable.

Specific work:
- add or update operator docs for Guidance authoring;
- document recovery from stale state, missing files, invalid refs, disabled mutations, and the major degraded states surfaced by the panel;
- add a release evidence checklist or smoke path for CAE authoring;
- keep this slice focused on operability guidance and release readiness rather than product behavior changes.

Out of scope:
- new product behavior;
- backend or dashboard feature work beyond what the docs and release gate need to reference;
- broad maintainer-doc reorganization unrelated to CAE authoring.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-21 (T100083), CAEUX-MVP-22 (T100084).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-22 as the bounded dashboard-test slice.

Goal: Prove the dashboard renders and drives the authoring loop.

Specific work:
- add render tests for empty, healthy, warning, disabled, and SQLite failure states;
- add message-handler tests for the supported create, update, preview, activate, disable, and retire entry points exposed by the panel;
- add a bounded manual or automated webview smoke path for the MVP authoring loop;
- avoid duplicating backend command-contract coverage that already belongs to the backend-test slice.

Out of scope:
- exhaustive end-to-end environment orchestration;
- re-testing backend command semantics already covered by MVP-21;
- unrelated extension UI coverage outside Guidance authoring.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-12 (T100074), CAEUX-MVP-13 (T100075), CAEUX-MVP-14 (T100076), CAEUX-MVP-15 (T100077), CAEUX-MVP-16 (T100078), CAEUX-MVP-17 (T100079), CAEUX-MVP-18 (T100080), CAEUX-MVP-19 (T100081), CAEUX-MVP-20 (T100082).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-21 as the bounded backend-test slice for CAE authoring commands.

Goal: Prove command behavior and mutation safety.

Specific work:
- add command-level tests for the artifact authoring flows already introduced by MVP-05 through MVP-08, including duplicate-default behavior where implemented;
- add command-level tests for draft activation create, update, activate, disable, and retire flows from MVP-09 through MVP-11;
- cover validation failures, referential integrity, audit rows, stale registry errors, and partial-write rollback at the backend contract level;
- keep fixtures and assertions stable enough for follow-on dashboard tasks to rely on these command contracts.

Out of scope:
- dashboard or webview interaction tests;
- broad end-to-end authoring-loop UI coverage;
- speculative tests for commands or payload shapes not yet delivered by the dependent backend tasks.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-05 (T100067), CAEUX-MVP-06 (T100068), CAEUX-MVP-07 (T100069), CAEUX-MVP-08 (T100070), CAEUX-MVP-09 (T100071), CAEUX-MVP-10 (T100072), CAEUX-MVP-11 (T100073).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-20 as the focused stale-state and failure-handling slice for the Guidance authoring panel.

Goal: Keep the UI safe when registry state changes or infrastructure is unavailable.

Specific work:
- surface stale registry save failures as explicit authoring conflicts with Refresh and Review Changes actions;
- render actionable degraded states for disabled CAE, JSON-store read-only mode, admin mutations off, missing DB/registry, and native SQLite load failures;
- ensure authoring forms and save affordances disable or reset once an unrecoverable authoring precondition fails;
- keep the panel legible and recoverable instead of falling back to blank or terminal-only failure modes.

Out of scope:
- implementing new mutation commands or backend recovery semantics;
- broad retry orchestration beyond refresh/review actions;
- unrelated dashboard UX cleanup outside the Guidance authoring surface.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-04 (T100066), CAEUX-MVP-12 (T100074).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-19 as the bounded mutation-confirmation and toast slice.

Goal: Make state-changing UI actions explicit and recoverable.

Specific work:
- add confirmation flows for activation publish, disable, retire, hide default, and artifact retire;
- capture `actor` and CAE mutation rationale where required by the backend contract;
- add result toasts with follow-up actions such as Open File, Preview, View Audit, and Refresh;
- keep the actual mutation logic in the existing editor, preview, and backend command flows.

Out of scope:
- backend mutation redesign;
- new authoring flows beyond confirmation and result feedback;
- dashboard-wide notification infrastructure unrelated to Guidance authoring.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-15 (T100077), CAEUX-MVP-17 (T100079), CAEUX-MVP-18 (T100080).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-18 as the bounded preview-tab and readiness-verdict slice.

Goal: Make activation impact understandable before publish.

Specific work:
- wire `cae-guidance-preview` with draft overlays from the activation editor;
- show baseline vs draft Guidance cards, family count deltas, broad-scope warnings, conflict summary, pending acknowledgements, and sample matches;
- show a bounded readiness verdict of OK, Warning, or Stop and confirm;
- produce fresh preview evidence that downstream publish and confirmation flows can consume.

Out of scope:
- publish confirmation UX;
- mutation-result toasts;
- broad simulation behavior beyond the current preview contract.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-11 (T100073), CAEUX-MVP-17 (T100079).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-17 as the bounded activation-editor and scope-builder slice.

Goal: Let users author activation rows without raw JSON as the default path.

Specific work:
- add structured form fields for activation ID, family, priority, lifecycle, artifact refs, acknowledgement, and scope;
- add preset controls for Always, command exact, command prefix, task tag, task ID pattern, phase key, and command arg equals;
- add an artifact picker grouped by type with source and status badges;
- add an advanced JSON drawer as an escape hatch rather than the default path.

Out of scope:
- publish gating and readiness verdict behavior;
- mutation confirmations and toasts;
- unsupported scope-builder semantics beyond the bounded preset set.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-09 (T100071), CAEUX-MVP-16 (T100078).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-16 as the bounded activations-table slice.

Goal: Give users a scannable management surface for CAE activation rows.

Specific work:
- add an activations table grouped by `policy`, `think`, `do`, and `review`;
- show lifecycle, priority, scope summary, artifact refs, acknowledgement, source, and status warnings;
- surface bounded row actions for Edit, Preview, Activate Draft, Disable, and Retire, plus Duplicate only if supported by the current backend contract;
- keep editor logic, publish gating, and confirmation UX in downstream slices.

Out of scope:
- activation editor implementation;
- publish confirmation or toast behavior;
- backend lifecycle redesign beyond current row-state needs.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-12 (T100074).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-15 as the bounded artifact-editor slice.

Goal: Let users create and edit workspace artifact metadata and markdown content.

Specific work:
- add a workspace-artifact form for ID, type, title, tags, path, and fragment;
- support markdown content editing or a bounded open-file workflow for workspace-owned files;
- add rendered or sanitized preview for the current workspace artifact draft;
- wire create, update, duplicate, and retire entry points to existing backend commands without allowing direct default edits.

Out of scope:
- mutation confirmation and toast UX;
- default-owned artifact editing;
- broader file-management flows such as arbitrary moves or rename orchestration.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-05 (T100067), CAEUX-MVP-06 (T100068), CAEUX-MVP-07 (T100069), CAEUX-MVP-14 (T100076).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-14 as the bounded artifacts-table slice.

Goal: Give users a scannable management surface for artifact rows and file refs.

Specific work:
- add a searchable and filterable artifacts table;
- show title, ID, type, source, path, used-by count, status, and last changed when available;
- expose row actions for Open, Preview, Duplicate, Edit, Retire, Hide Default, and Remove Override only when source and lifecycle state make them valid;
- keep editor, confirmation, and mutation-result UX in downstream tasks.

Out of scope:
- implementing the artifact editor itself;
- confirmation or toast behavior for row actions;
- backend contract changes beyond the row-state needs of the table.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-12 (T100074).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-12 as the dedicated Guidance authoring panel shell task.

Goal: Add a first-class editor-area Guidance authoring panel.

Specific work:
- add a dedicated command/view entry point for Guidance authoring in the editor area;
- render a stable panel shell with tabs for Overview, Artifacts, Activations, Preview, and compact Audit;
- wire panel readiness and refresh to `cae-authoring-summary` as the single summary contract for this slice;
- show actionable degraded states for disabled CAE, missing DB/registry, native SQLite failures, and registry validation failures.

Out of scope:
- in-panel artifact or activation CRUD;
- bespoke business logic in the webview beyond presenting the summary contract;
- broad auto-refresh/watcher behavior beyond the minimal panel bootstrap and refresh path already supported by extension infrastructure.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-03 (T100065).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-10 as a constrained lifecycle-integrity slice for activations.

Goal: Expose safe lifecycle changes for active and draft activations.

Specific work:
- add dedicated disable/retire wrappers or command responses for UI lifecycle use rather than requiring the panel to compose raw lifecycle transitions;
- support only the conservative transitions needed for current draft and active activation flows;
- return affected artifact refs and resulting lifecycle state so the UI can trigger immediate preview verification;
- ensure disabled and retired activations no longer affect preview and effective evaluation paths.

Out of scope:
- restore or re-enable flows;
- implicit cascade updates to related activations or artifacts;
- broader lifecycle redesign beyond the current disable/retire needs.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-09 (T100071).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Rewrite CAEUX-MVP-07 as a narrow backend slice for default-to-workspace duplication.

Goal: Let users start from shipped defaults without mutating them.

Specific work:
- add a dedicated `cae-duplicate-default-artifact` command for duplicating default-owned artifacts into the workspace layer;
- require caller-supplied `workspace.*` artifact IDs and deterministic slug-to-path derivation under `.ai/cae/artifacts/<type>/`;
- capture default provenance such as `sourceDefaultArtifactId` and `sourceContentHash` without mutating the shipped default row;
- return dashboard-friendly artifact/ref payloads for follow-on UI tasks.

Out of scope:
- dashboard invocation flow or modal UX;
- arbitrary target-path selection;
- automatic conflict renaming.

Blocked by: CAEUX-MVP-05 (T100067).

Use the supported workspace-kit command path for task, CAE registry, and dashboard changes; do not hand-edit kit-owned state.

Goal: Establish the shared task-engine configuration foundation for configurable maintainer delivery and task intake requirements.

Specific work:
- add task-engine-owned config registry keys for maintainerDelivery and tasks.intakePolicy;
- define profile, override, and enforcement-mode shapes for delivery and intake policies;
- keep the built-in default equivalent to the current GitHub PR phase-branch delivery flow and current task validation behavior;
- document precedence as task override, module override, workspace default, then built-in default;
- validate enum values, tokenized branch/tag patterns, profile references, and module override structure.

Blockers: none. This is the foundation slice for the rest of the policy work.
